=========================================================
C++ TYPE CONVERSION INTERVIEW NOTES (MOST ASKED)
=========================================================

C++ supports three types of conversions:

1. Primitive Type  -> Class Type
2. Class Type      -> Primitive Type
3. Class Type      -> Class Type


=========================================================
1. PRIMITIVE TYPE -> CLASS TYPE
=========================================================

Uses:
Conversion Constructor

Syntax:

class Test
{
public:
    Test(int x);
};

Example:

Test obj = 10;

Compiler converts it to:

Test obj = Test(10);

Interview Q:
-------------
Q. How do you convert a primitive type into a class object?

A.
Using a Conversion Constructor.

Example:

Test(int);


=========================================================
2. CLASS TYPE -> PRIMITIVE TYPE
=========================================================

Uses:
Conversion Operator (Casting Operator)

Syntax:

operator int() const ****vvvvimp we have operator keyword first *****
{
    return value;
}

Example:

Test obj(100);

int x = obj;

Compiler converts it to:

int x = obj.operator int();

Interview Q:
-------------
Q. How do you convert a class object into a primitive type?

A.
Using a Conversion Operator.

Example:

operator int();

Common examples:

operator int();
operator bool();


Important Points
----------------
• No return type is written.
• No parameters are allowed.
• Usually declared const.

Correct:

operator int() const;

Wrong:

int operator int();


=========================================================
3. CLASS TYPE -> CLASS TYPE
=========================================================

There are TWO approaches.


Approach 1 : Conversion Constructor
-----------------------------------

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Product
{
private:
    int m, n;

public:
    Product(int x = 0, int y = 0)
    {
        m = x;
        n = y;
    }

    int getM() const { return m; }
    int getN() const { return n; }
};

class Item
{
private:
    int a, b;

public:
    Item()
    {
        a = 0;
        b = 0;
    }

    // Conversion Constructor (KEY PART)
    Item(Product p)
    {
        a = p.getM();
        b = p.getN();
    }

    void show()
    {
        cout << "a = " << a << ", b = " << b << endl;
    }
};

int main()
{
    Product p1(10, 20);

    Item i1 = p1;   // Class -> Class conversion

    i1.show();

    return 0;
}


Approach 2 : Conversion Operator
--------------------------------

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Item;

class Product
{
private:
    int m, n;

public:
    Product(int x = 0, int y = 0)
    {
        m = x;
        n = y;
    }

    int getM() const { return m; }
    int getN() const { return n; }

    // Conversion Operator
    operator Item();
};

class Item
{
private:
    int a, b;

public:
    Item()
    {
        a = 0;
        b = 0;
    }

    Item(int x, int y)
    {
        a = x;
        b = y;
    }

    void show()
    {
        cout << "a = " << a << ", b = " << b << endl;
    }

    friend class Product;
};

// definition of conversion operator
Product::operator Item()
{
    return Item(m, n);
}

int main()
{
    Product p1(10, 20);

    Item i1 = p1;   // Class -> Class conversion

    i1.show();

    return 0;
}




=========================================================
MOST ASKED INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
=========================================================

Q. What are the three types of conversions in C++?

A.
1. Primitive -> Class
2. Class -> Primitive
3. Class -> Class

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. How do you convert Primitive -> Class?

A.
Using a Conversion Constructor.

Example:

Test(int);

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. How do you convert Class -> Primitive?

A.
Using a Conversion Operator.

Example:

operator int();

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. How do you convert Class -> Class?

A.
Two ways:

1. Conversion Constructor

2. Conversion Operator

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. What does

int x = obj;

become?

A.

int x = obj.operator int();

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Can a Conversion Operator have a return type?

A.
No.

Correct:

operator int();

Wrong:

int operator int();

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Can a Conversion Operator take parameters?

A.
No.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Can a Conversion Operator be const?

A.
Yes.

Usually:

operator int() const;

